TI  - Landsliding and Its Multiscale Influence on Mountainscapes
T2  - BIOSCIENCE
LA  - English
KW  - landslides
KW  - biotic and geomorphic processes
KW  - mountains
KW  - conservation
KW  - LAND-COVER
KW  - VEGETATION
KW  - FOREST
KW  - SOIL
KW  - DISTURBANCE
KW  - SUCCESSION
KW  - RECOVERY
AB  - Landsliding is a complex process that modifies mountainscapes worldwide. Its severe and sometimes long-lasting negative effects contrast with the less-documented positive effects on ecosystems, raising numerous questions about the dual role of landsliding, the feedbacks between biotic and geomorphic processes, and, ultimately, the ecological and evolutionary responses of organisms. We present a conceptual model in which feedbacks between biotic and geomorphic processes, landslides, and ecosystem attributes are hypothesized to drive the dynamics of mountain ecosystems at multiple scales. This model is used to integrate and synthesize a rich, but fragmented, body of literature generated in different disciplines, and to highlight the need for profitable collaborations between biologists and geoscientists. Such efforts should help identify attributes that contribute to the resilience of mountain ecosystems, and also should help in conservation, restoration, and hazard assessment. Given the sensitivity of mountains to land-use and global climate change, these endeavors are both relevant and timely.
