TI  - ECOLOGY OF A WOODLAND BUTTERFLY WITH NEAR-THREATENED STATUS, <i>SASAKIA CHARONDA</i>, (LEPIDOPTERA, NYMPHALIDAE) AND MANAGEMENT OF RIPARIAN AND SECONDARY BROADLEAF DECIDUOUS FORESTS FOR CONSERVATION OF THE BUTTERFLY
T2  - INSECT HABITATS: CHARACTERISTICS, DIVERSITY AND MANAGEMENT
LA  - English
KW  - PARARGE-AEGERIA
KW  - PIERIS-RAPAE
KW  - FRAGMENTED LANDSCAPES
KW  - HABITAT FRAGMENTATION
KW  - PROCLOSSIANA-EUNOMIA
KW  - EUPHYDRYAS-MATURNA
KW  - PUDDLING BEHAVIOR
KW  - HESPERIA-COMMA
KW  - FORMICA-RUFA
KW  - POPULATION
AB  - To clarify forest management plan for conservation of the woodland butterfly, Sasakia charonda, the near-threatened species in Japan, we investigated the population ecology of the butterfly and its host trees, Celtis sinensis and Celtis jessoensis, in riparian forests and the surrounding secondary broadleaf deciduous forests before used and managed for production of firewood and charcoal (hereafter, secondary forests). Riparian forests regenerated by floods and/or landslides functioned as sites for regeneration of host trees, for courting, puddling and egg laying behaviors of adult butterflies, and for habitats of the butterfly larvae. While, secondary forests located behind riparian forests functioned as sites for roosting behaviors of adult female and for sipping tree sap by adult males. Therefore, the original habitat of S. charonda is probably a riparian forest and we found that the landscape with both riparian and secondary forest habitats had important roles in the maintenance of the butterfly and its host tree populations. Consequently, the recommended habitat management for conserving the butterfly populations is the ensuring of sufficient width in riverbed for guaranteeing the event of natural disturbances and the reductions in the construction of barriers to prevent landslides and concrete shore embankments together with the securing of secondary forests. On the other hand, in the habitats consisted of only secondary forests, which are considered to be functioned as alternative habitats of S. charonda instead of riparian forests, many adult S. charonda sipped tree sap of Quercus acutissima. C. sinensis trees regenerated at the edges of secondary forests newly established by partial deforestation. Thus, although the partial deforestation of secondary forests with the alteration in traditional land use decrease the total area of secondary forests, it created new forest edges and led to the increase in the number of the host trees. However, contrary to this, such deforestation led to the decrease in the densities of both larvae and adults of the butterfly. Thus, the habitat requirements of S. charonda and its host trees are contrary each other. To compound these contrasting habitat requirements, it is necessary to create new forest edges continuously in a given habitat without decreasing total area of secondary forests. Therefore, in secondary forest habitats, recommended management for conserving the butterfly populations is traditional coppicing that secondary forests containing stands of Q. acutissima and host trees are divided into several blocks and these blocks are cyclically and sequentially deforested without decreasing total area of secondary forests.
