TI  - Landform restoration in an anthropogenically disturbed and tectonically active area
T2  - PROCEEDINGS OF CONFERENCE 29 - INTERNATIONAL EROSION CONTROL ASSOCIATION
LA  - English
CP  - Conference 29 of the International-Erosion-Control-Association on Winning Solutions for Risky Problems
AB  - Bull Creek watershed, located within Humboldt Redwoods State Park, Northern California, is home of the Rockefeller Forest of ancient Redwoods. The combination of steep slopes in the upper watershed (50% to > 70%), low gradients along Bull Creek Flats (flat to 10%), highly erodible soils, weak sedimentary bedrock, heavy annual precipitation, and past landuse make this 106 km(2) (41 mi(2)) watershed susceptible to severe erosion and sedimentation. Following logging and burning in the upper watershed, and flooding in 1955 and 1964, erosion rates increased significantly.
   California State Parks (CSP) employed several workers, including C. Gleason, W. Lowdermilk, H. Einstein, D. Rosgen, and L. Leopold to remediate erosion and channel instability problems. Results of this work involved land acquisition and channel manipulation, while relying on natural revegetation to restore hydrologic integrity to the upper watershed. Channel instability in lower Bull Creek caused toppling of about 850 ancient Redwoods, leading to acquisition of the upper watershed by CSP in the late 1960's. Riprap placed along lower Bull Creek Flats has protected most of the Rockefeller Forest from further erosion. Vegetative regeneration in the upper watershed has reduced sheetwash erosion; however, other processes are delivering large quantities of sediment. Until sedimentation returns to a more natural rate continued use of riprap in lower Bull Creek Fiats is anticipated.
   To reduce erosion and sedimentation CSP has initiated a landform restoration program. Restoration design and implementation are prioritized by identifying active erosion sources and areas of potential risk through geomorphic mapping and development of sediment budgets for subwatersheds to Bull Creek. For restoration treatments requiring road removal, geomorphic mapping provides the blueprint to re-establish pre-anthropogenic disturbance conditions and is essential for identifying stable fill storage locations. Diversion of subsurface and surface water flow by abandoned logging roads and skid trails has been identified as the most treatable disturbance. These disturbances extend the natural drainage network, thus resulting in extensive gullies, inner gorge failures, and reactivation of ancient landslides. Rates of road surface erosion appear to have declined in response to post-logging vegetative recovery. However, estimates of sediment production suggest recently reactivated landslides currently contribute at least 25 times as much sediment as road surface erosion and fill failures.
   Combined costs for brush removal, recontouring road prisms, and spreading masticated brush averages $17.7 per linear meter ($5.4 ft) of road. This cost is for a dozer and an excavator, weighing approximately 22,000 kg (50,000 Ib) each, recontouring roads averaging 6.7 meters (22 ft) wide with moderate to heavy brush conditions.
