TI  - Quasi-optimum redistribution of empty PRT vehicles
T2  - AUTOMATED PEOPLE MOVERS VI: CREATIVE ACCESS FOR MAJOR ACTIVITY CENTERS
LA  - English
CP  - 6th International Conference on Automated People Movers
AB  - The task of redistributing empty vehicles in a PRT system is particularly difficult in peak periods and in large networks.
   Simulations of PRT systems often have a vehicle management component based on sequential choices of vehicles called to a station with a deficit. We have tested various rules for call and send based on expected levels at other stations and the time required to bring a vehicle from a surplus to a deficit. Different planning horizons are used for each station based on the average call time (successive estimations) to that station.
   Balancing supply and demand in a transport network at minimum cost (minimum empty running) is well-known in optimization, the so called "transportation problem". The classic transportation problem is a static equilibrium problem where time is not a concern. Deficits and surpluses in PRT networks however evolve successively at random times with a need to take immidiate decisions.
